<b>Chicken Vesuvio,</b> a specialty of <village wordnetid="108672738" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../886/6886.xml">
Chicago</link></village>
, is an <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../621/3644621.xml">
Italian-American</link> dish made from <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../402/37402.xml">
chicken</link> on the bone and wedges of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../501/23501.xml">
potato</link>, sauteed with <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../469/50469.xml">
garlic</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../266/22266.xml">
oregano</link>, white <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../961/32961.xml">
wine</link> and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../478/22478.xml">
olive oil</link>, then baked till the chicken's skin crisps. The dish is often garnished with a few green <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../407/59407.xml">
pea</link>s for color. <p>

In Chicago, one also often finds the savory technique applied to other foods, like "<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../945/61945.xml">
steak</link> Vesuvio," "<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../503/1621503.xml">
pork chop</link>s Vesuvio" or even just "Vesuvio potatoes."</p>
<p>

The origins of the dish are unknown, but some suggest it might have been popularized by the Vesuvio Restaurant, which operated at 15 E. <road wordnetid="104096066" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../190/1492190.xml">
Wacker Drive</link></road>
, Chicago, in the 1930s.</p>

